         <div type="commentary" subtype="general">
            <p>The Greek text comes from PHerc 1077, Roll B, which are part of a larger collection of 12 fragments in a glass casing. The 12 fragments were mis-identified as all coming from Philodemus, De pietate. But Bassi and Cavallo noticed early that the handwriting of the fragments were different and conjectured that these came from different authors. Dorandi has identified 4 different rolls based on the handwriting and PHerc 1077 has been re-identified as follows: Roll A, fragments 1-6 (originally fragments 1, 2, 4, 5, 6, 7) are from Philodemus, Rhetorica IV, PHerc 1007, 1673; Roll B fragments 1-4 (originally fragments 8, 9, 10, 12) are from Philodemus, De aviditate, PHerc 253, 465, 896,1613; Roll C fragment 1 (originally fragment 3) is uncertain and might be from Philodemus, De pietate; Roll D fragments 1-2 (originally fragment 11 in 2 parts) might be the only true fragment from Philodemus, De pietate, PHerc 1077. The text presented here is Roll B fragments 1-4 as published by Tiziano Dorandi, "Fragmenta Herculanensia inedita," ZPE, 71 (1988), pp. 47-48 (no original photographs provided).</p>
